(appendix
  :book \"book-of-motion\"
  :number 8
  :title \"Stop-Motion and Independent Traditions\"
  :short-title \"stop-motion-and-independent\"
  :estimated-words 1400
  :philosopher-weave (aristotle sartre peirce wittgenstein-late)

  :prose
\"Stop-motion animation is a specific physical practice. A three-dimensional object — a puppet, a clay figure, a manipulated real-world scene — is photographed. The object is moved a small amount. Another photograph is taken. Repeat many thousands of times. When the sequence of photographs is played back, the object appears to move on its own.

This is a very old technique. Georges Méliès used stop-motion for special effects in the 1890s and 1900s. Willis O'Brien pioneered stop-motion for feature films with *The Lost World* (1925) and *King Kong* (1933). Ray Harryhausen carried O'Brien's tradition into the 1950s and 1960s with a series of adventure and fantasy features (*Jason and the Argonauts*, 1963; *The 7th Voyage of Sinbad*, 1958). Every one of the mythological creatures in those films was a small puppet, animated one frame at a time.

# Ray Harryhausen and the fantastic

Harryhausen (1920-2013) called his work *Dynamation*. His technique combined stop-motion puppets with live-action footage: the puppets were animated against a rear-projected film of live actors, so the finished shot showed puppets and actors interacting as if they were in the same space. In *Jason and the Argonauts*, the famous skeleton fight took Harryhausen four months to animate — seven skeletons versus three actors, each skeleton moving independently, all synchronized to the live actors' sword-fight choreography.

Harryhausen worked mostly alone. His puppets were small — a foot or two tall. He built them from wire armatures with foam-rubber musculature and painted latex skin. He animated them by moving each puppet incrementally between exposures. A single day of work produced perhaps a few seconds of finished animation.

# The Aardman tradition

Peter Lord and David Sproxton founded Aardman Animations in Bristol, England, in 1972. Aardman developed a distinctive style using plasticine (a modeling clay) for figures and elaborate physical sets. Their television shorts of the 1980s — including *Creature Comforts* (1989), directed by Nick Park — established the studio's approach, and Park's *Wallace and Gromit* series (starting with *A Grand Day Out*, 1989) brought Aardman to worldwide attention.

Aardman's technique involves molding plasticine figures with movable armatures inside, photographing them one frame at a time, and adjusting facial expressions by hand for each frame. Each character's face is often replaced with a slightly different sculpted version for each dialogue-frame, giving the specific plasticine-fingermark quality that Aardman films are famous for. If you look closely at a Wallace and Gromit shot, you can often see the thumbprints in Wallace's face — small marks left by the animator's fingers pressing the clay into the required expression.

Aardman later made features (*Chicken Run*, 2000; *Wallace & Gromit: The Curse of the Were-Rabbit*, 2005; *Flushed Away*, 2006) and continues to produce stop-motion work into the 2020s.

# Laika and the American revival

Laika, based in Portland, Oregon and founded in 2005 as a stop-motion feature studio, has continued the practice at feature scale in the 2010s. Their films *Coraline* (2009), *ParaNorman* (2012), *The Boxtrolls* (2014), *Kubo and the Two Strings* (2016), and *Missing Link* (2019) use stop-motion combined with computer techniques for elements that would be too difficult to build physically (large-scale environmental effects, some crowd shots, digital replacement of visible armatures).

Laika's puppets are highly engineered. Each character has an armature designed for specific ranges of motion, sculpted faces printed with 3D printers so that dozens of subtly different facial expressions can be swapped in per shot, and rigging systems that hold the puppet in position between exposures. A Laika feature typically takes four to five years to produce.

# The Quay Brothers and Jan Švankmajer

At the more experimental end of stop-motion is the tradition of dark, surreal, symbol-heavy animation exemplified by the American twin brothers Stephen and Timothy Quay (working from London since the 1970s) and by the Czech animator Jan Švankmajer.

The Quays' films — *Street of Crocodiles* (1986), *The Comb* (1990), *In Absentia* (2000) among many others — use stop-motion of dolls, mannequins, dust, hair, screws, and other found objects. Their work has a specific atmosphere: unsettling, tactile, dreamlike. They are more influenced by Central European visual traditions than by American animation.

Švankmajer (born 1934), working from Prague since the 1960s, uses stop-motion of live actors, meat, clay, and everyday objects. His films (*Dimensions of Dialogue*, 1982; *Alice*, 1988; *Faust*, 1994) are politically and psychologically complex, often engaging with childhood, appetite, and totalitarianism. He is one of the most important experimental filmmakers of the second half of the twentieth century.

Both the Quays and Švankmajer show that stop-motion can be adult, complex, and deeply psychological — a medium capable of representing what other techniques cannot.

# What stop-motion has that other techniques don't

Stop-motion has specific qualities that computer animation and hand-drawn animation cannot easily replicate.

**Physical light on physical objects.** Stop-motion puppets are real objects in real space. When light falls on them, it falls with the specific physical character of real light: shadows, reflections, subsurface scattering through translucent materials. This gives stop-motion a tactile presence that hand-drawn animation cannot fully achieve and that computer animation must expensively simulate.

**Materiality.** The puppets have weight, texture, and physical mass. When they interact with other objects, they push against them. The physical interactions have a substance that drawn interactions lack.

**Fingerprints of the animator.** Because the puppets are handled by human animators, they carry marks of that handling — thumbprints in clay, wear patterns in fabric, small distortions in silhouette from being manipulated. These marks give stop-motion its characteristic hand-made quality.

**Time-heaviness.** Stop-motion is slow to produce. A minute of finished animation might take a week or two of work. This slowness is often visible in the final work — the pacing, the deliberateness, the sense that every frame was earned.

For an animator, the choice to use stop-motion is a choice for these qualities. It is not the fastest or the cheapest technique, but it produces effects that other techniques struggle to achieve.

# What we can do in Scheme

We cannot really do stop-motion in Scheme — the technique requires physical objects and cameras. But we can simulate its rhythmic characteristics.

```scheme
;; Stop-motion animation typically runs at 12 or 24 fps but each frame is a
;; discrete, held pose — no in-between motion blur. We can simulate this by
;; using stepped positions rather than continuous motion.

(define (stop-motion-step t total-time discrete-frames)
  ;; Given continuous time t, snap it to one of the discrete frames.
  (let* ((frame-duration (/ total-time discrete-frames))
         (frame-index (floor (/ t frame-duration))))
    (/ frame-index discrete-frames)))

(define (stop-motion-walk duration)
  (let ((discrete-frames 12))    ; 12 discrete poses across the walk
    (let loop ((t 0))
      (when (< t duration)
        (let* ((discrete-t (stop-motion-step t duration discrete-frames))
               (x (+ 100 (* discrete-t 400))))
          (world/reset!)
          (world/place-puppet x 300 'walking-pose (floor (* discrete-t 12)))
          (world/render!)
          (world/wait (/ 1.0 24.0))
          (loop (+ t (/ 1.0 24.0))))))))

(stop-motion-walk 3.0)
```

The character moves in discrete 'stepped' positions rather than continuously. When played back, the motion has the specific staccato character of stop-motion — the character appears to jump from one held pose to the next, with no smooth transition between. This is what stop-motion actually looks like on screen, and it is part of its charm: the visible discreteness of the frames makes the medium's physical practice legible.

# Recommended viewing

*Jason and the Argonauts* (1963). Harryhausen's skeleton fight.

*Wallace & Gromit: The Wrong Trousers* (Nick Park, 1993). Aardman's most complete early masterpiece.

*Coraline* (Henry Selick, 2009). Laika's first feature; a serious dark fantasy for children.

*Kubo and the Two Strings* (Travis Knight, 2016). Laika at its most ambitious.

*Street of Crocodiles* (Quay Brothers, 1986). Twenty minutes of dark, tactile, sound-designed stop-motion.

*Dimensions of Dialogue* (Švankmajer, 1982). One of the most technically inventive short animated films ever made.

# Sources cited

Ken A. Priebe, *The Advanced Art of Stop-Motion Animation* (Cengage Learning, 2011).

Peter Lord and Brian Sibley, *Cracking Animation: The Aardman Book of 3-D Animation* (Thames & Hudson, 1998; later editions).

Julius Wiedemann, ed., *Animation Now!* (Taschen, 2004). Overview of contemporary independent animation.

Michael Brooke, *The Quay Brothers* (Illuminations Films documentary, 2000).\"

  :notes
\"All named individuals (Harryhausen, Peter Lord, David Sproxton, Nick Park, Quay Brothers, Švankmajer, Willis O'Brien, Méliès) and studios (Aardman, Laika) are historically documented with their films and dates. King Kong (1933) O'Brien attribution is standard. Jason and the Argonauts (1963) Harryhausen skeleton fight is famous and documented. All films cited are widely-verifiable via their studios' or directors' filmographies. Aardman and Laika treated as artistic movements rather than corporate entities; specific film credits (directors) attributed correctly.\"

  :philosopher-weave-details
\"Aristotle: stop-motion as an action executed through many small acts, each a physical intervention.
Sartre: the animator's being is the puppet's being — the puppet moves because the animator moved it, in a very direct sense.
Peirce: the puppet on film as index — the physical trace of the animator's hand is captured directly on the film.
Wittgenstein-late: stop-motion as a distinct language-game the audience learns to read — the stepped motion is not a flaw but a feature the medium teaches its viewers to enjoy.\"

  :tie-forward
\"The Book of Motion appendices close here. The other books in the reading order — Book of Words, Book of Reason — pick up literary and philosophical material.\")
